Boil a full #kettle{}. Pour the boiled water into a #medium saucepan{} with
@salt{1/2%tsp} and bring back to the boil.

When boiling, add the @macaroni{90%g} to the water and bring back to the boil.
Cook until tender, ~{12%minutes}.

Reserve some pasta water in a #jug{}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back into the pan with a drizzle of
@oil{drizzle} to stop it sticking together.

While the pasta cooks, peel and chop the @onion{1} into small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a #large saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

When hot, add the onion to the pan and stir-fry until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add the @roasted spice and herb blend{1}, @tomato passata{1}, @vegetable stock
paste{10%g}, @reserved pasta water{350%ml} and @sugar{1}. Stir to combine.

Stir the @baby spinach{100%g} into the soup a handful at a time until wilted.

Bring to the boil, then reduce the heat and simmer until the spinach is
piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Meanwhile, grate the @mature cheddar cheese{40%g}.

Drain and rinse the @mixed beans{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

Stir the cooked macaroni, beans and @fresh pesto{50%g} into the soup.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed.

Add a splash of @water{} if it's a little thick.

Share your spring minestrone between your #bowls{}.

Sprinkle over the cheese to finish.

> Our Spring Minestrone is a delicious veggie option that makes it easy to
> eat more veg in your diet and try something new!